Lot of difference here.<br>
 If we assay a stretch of the Moon's surface, or thoroughly study a smallish asteroid, then there's nthing wrong with mining it.<br>
 &quot;Rugged natural beauty&quot; gets boring pretty quick, if it's gravel, sand, rocks, more sand, more roks, and nothing else except a bunch of random samplings taken for photomicrographs to really study it.<br>
 That football-field-sized strip mine is identical to what the same spot or any other spot on the Moon has gone through before and will again, a few million years from now when a big rock smashes into it at a few miles/sec. Nothing we can do to it that hasn't happened before.<br>
 The Moons surface is pretty much a hodgepodge of stuff mixed up &amp; overlapped by impacts. Once you study a spot to see if there's anything different &amp; worth more study, there's not much reason to come back, and plenty of places that might be more photogenic, whenever tourists get up there.<br>
